05974nam a22009015i 9780812208191DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20132013pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1024008084  a(OCoLC)1037980459  a(OCoLC)1042028269  a(OCoLC)1046605258  a(OCoLC)1047000577  a(OCoLC)1049627165  a(OCoLC)1054872294  a97808122081917 a10.9783/97808122081912doi  a(DE-B1597)449689  a(OCoLC)979684966  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPS3505.O763bR4 1981 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a811/.542191 aShoulson, Jeffrey S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFictions of Conversion :bJews, Christians, and Cultures of Change in Early Modern England /cJeffrey S. Shoulson. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. “The Jews Perverted and the Gentiles Converted”: Confessions and Conversos -- tChapter 2. “Thy People Shall Be My People”: Typology, Gender, and Biblical Converts -- tChapter 3. “The Meaning, Not the Name I Call”: Converting the Bible and Homer -- tChapter 4. Alchemies of Conversion: Shakespeare, Jonson, Vaughan, and the Science of Jewish Transmutation -- tChapter 5. Conversion and Enthusiasm: Radical Religion and the Poetics of Paradise Regained -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe fraught history of England's Long Reformation is a convoluted if familiar story: in the space of twenty-five years, England changed religious identity three times. In 1534 England broke from the papacy with the Act of Supremacy that made Henry VIII head of the church; nineteen years later the act was overturned by his daughter Mary, only to be reinstated at the ascension of her half-sister Elizabeth. Buffeted by political and confessional cross-currents, the English discovered that conversion was by no means a finite, discrete process. In Fictions of Conversion, Jeffrey S. Shoulson argues that the vagaries of religious conversion were more readily negotiated when they were projected onto an alien identity—one of which the potential for transformation offered both promise and peril but which could be kept distinct from the emerging identity of Englishness: the Jew.Early modern Englishmen and -women would have recognized an uncannily familiar religious chameleon in the figure of the Jewish converso, whose economic, social, and political circumstances required religious conversion, conformity, or counterfeiting. Shoulson explores this distinctly English interest in the Jews who had been exiled from their midst nearly three hundred years earlier, contending that while Jews held out the tantalizing possibility of redemption through conversion, the trajectory of falling in and out of divine favor could be seen to anticipate the more recent trajectory of England's uncertain path of reformation. In translations such as the King James Bible and Chapman's Homer, dramas by Marlowe, Shakespeare, and Jonson, and poetry by Donne, Vaughan, and Milton, conversion appears as a cypher for and catalyst of other transformations—translation, alchemy, and the suspect religious enthusiasm of the convert—that preoccupy early modern English cultures of change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAmerican poetry. 0aChristianity and other religionsxJudaismxHistoryy17th century. 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aJews in literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aReligion and literaturezEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 4aReligious Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Iri